    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <head>Biographical History</head>
      <p>Burges Green (1912-1981) was an American editorial cartoonist. </p>
      <p>Green was born June 16, 1912 and was the nephew of U.S. Senator Theodore Green of Rhode Island. Green worked for the <emph render="italic">Providence Journal</emph> as editorial cartoonist until 1970. He also illustrated "American Literature in Parody: A Collection of Parody, Satire and Literary Burlesque of American Writers Past and Present" (Twayne 1955)</p>
      <p>Green died in June 1981.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
      <p>The 
        
        <emph render="bold">Burges Green Cartoons</emph> consist entirely of editorial cartoons documenting national, international and local politics.  </p>
      <p>
        The <emph render="bold">Cartoons</emph> series contains approximately 4,845 original editorial cartoons from 1949 to 1970 and one proof. </p>
      <p>Items typically measure 12 1/4" x 17 1/2". Green worked in ink, primarily on Craftint paper. Traces of pencil are visible; captions and date information appear in blue pencil. Green's style emphasized thin lines and little shading; a limited number of cartoons feature crayon shading. </p>
    </scopecontent>
